ed with Monte or Monti. Compare   Del Monte  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Monti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Aniello, Pasquale, Aldo, Carmel, Elio, Enrico, Gaetano, Marco, Marino, Philomena.","Italian: variant of   Monte  , from the plural."]},{"name":"Montagna","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Sal, Gaetano, Alessandro, Antonino, Attilio, Carlo, Carmelo, Cosmo, Dino, Enrico, Oreste.","Italian: topographic name for someone who lived on or near a mountain or mountains, Italian <i>montagna</i>, from Late Latin <i>montanea</i>, originally the neuter plural of an adjective derivative of <i>mons</i> (see   Monte   1), or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word."]},{"name":"Montini","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Enio, Pietro, Arsenio, Concetta, Dante, Dino, Domenic, Eliseo, Lorenzo, Marco, Mauro, Quirino, Ricco, Tulio.","Italian (Milan):","patronymic or plural form of a diminutive of   Monte  ."]},{"name":"Montes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Jorge, Luis, Francisco, Miguel, Carlos, Alfredo, Ramon, Raul.  Portuguese Joaquim.","Spanish (also <b>Montés</b>); Portuguese (also <b>Montês</b>): topographic name for a mountain dweller, from the plural form of   Monte   ‘mountain’ or from the adjective Spanish <i>montés</i>, Portuguese <i>montês</i> ‘of the mountain’."]},{"name":"Montello","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Biagio, Carmela, Marco.","Italian: from a diminutive of   Monte  ."]},{"name":"Del Monte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gaspar, Angelo, Rocco, Giovanni, Pompeo, Antonio, Armelio, Berta, Camillo, Carmela, Deno, Elvio, Ezio, Gilda, Giulio.  Spanish Angel, Gonzalo, Guillermina, Jesus, Jose, Jose Manuel.","Italian, Spanish, and Jewish (from Italy): variant, with the preposition and definite article <i>del</i> ‘from the’, of   Monte  .","Jewish (Sephardic): 